{{Infobox military person | name = Breffu | other_name = Baeffu, Beafuu, Beffru | nickname = Queen of St John | birth_place = [[Akwamu]], [[Ghana]] | death_date = {{Death date|1734|05|}} | death_place = [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|St. Jan, Danish West Indies]] | allegiance = [[1733 slave insurrection on St. John|Akwamu Insurrection]] }}
'''Breffu''' was an [[Akwamu]] leader of the [[1733 slave insurrection on St. John]] (then known as ''St. Jan'') in [[Danish West Indies]]. She committed suicide with 23 other rebels to evade capture as the rebellion weakened in 1734.
==St Jan Slave Insurrection== Breffu was enslaved at a plantation owned by Pieter Krøyer, and lived in [[Coral Bay, U.S. Virgin Islands|Coral Bay]].{{sfnp|Norton|2013|p=300}} On 23 November 1733, hearing the signal of a canon fired from Fort Fredericksvaern, Breffu entered the main house and killed both Krøyer and his wife. Taking all gunpowder and ammunition, and accompanied by fellow slave Christian, Breffu then proceeded to the Van Stell family house, where she killed three members of the plantation owner's family.{{sfnp|Norton|2013|p=69}}
She committed suicide to evade capture,<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/mar/20/breffu-a-slave-a-rebel-a-fighter-and-a-woman-almost-invisible-to-history|title=Breffu: a slave, a rebel, a fighter – and a woman almost invisible to history|author=Holly Norton|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 March 2018|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> and is thought to have died in either April or May of 1734.{{sfnp|Norton|2013|p=300}} Her body was discovered at Browns Bay, along with another 23 rebels who committed suicide, at which a plantation owner recorded his surprise that, "one of the leaders of the rebellion, Baeffu, whom none of us knew, and whom we assumed to be a man having murdered my son Pieter Krøyer and his wife, is a woman!"{{sfnp|Norton|2013|p=90}}
==In popular culture== Breffu has been dramatised as the "Queen of St John" in the play ''Three Queens Chautauqua Series: Act I Queen Breffu''.<ref name=tradewinds>{{cite web|url=https://www.stjohntradewinds.com/three-local-queens-embodied-in-chautauqua-series/|title=Three Local Queens Embodied in Chautauqua Series|author=St. John Tradewinds|publisher=St. John Tradewinds|date=19 June 2006|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> In a 2006 production, Breffu was portrayed by the academic Jaweh David.<ref name=tradewinds/> She has also featured as a subject in festival floats at St John celebrations.<ref name=tradewinds1>{{cite web|url=https://www.stjohntradewinds.com/new-troupes-dance-through-cruz-bay-alongside-old-favorites-at-60th-anniversary-festival-parade/|title=New Troupes Dance Through Cruz Bay Alongside Old Favorites at 60th Anniversary Festival Parade|author=Andrea Milam|publisher=St. John Tradewinds|date=5 July 2014|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref>
