{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox rugby league biography |name = Jerry Brien |fullname = Jerome Albert Brien |image = |caption = |birth_date = 1900 |birth_place = [[Sydney, Australia]] |death_date = 1962 |height = |weight = |position = {{rlp|HB}} |club1 = [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests Magpies]] |year1start = 1923 |year1end = 28 |appearances1 = 39 |tries1 = 8 |goals1 = 1 |fieldgoals1 = 0 |points1 = 26 |club2 = [[St. George Dragons|St George]] |year2start = 1929 |year2end = |appearances2 = 4 |tries2 = 0 |goals2 = 0 |fieldgoals2 = 0 |points2 = 0 |retired = yes |teamA = [[New South Wales state rugby league team|New South Wales]] |yearAstart = 1925 |yearAend = 28 |appearancesA = 3 |triesA = 0 |goalsA = 0 |fieldgoalsA = 0 |pointsA = 0 |coachteam1 = [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Wests Magpies]] |coachyear1start = 1937 |coachyear1end = |coachgames1 = 8 |coachwins1 = 3 |coachdraws1 = 0 |coachlosses1 = 55 |coachteam2 = [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Canterbury Bulldogs]] |coachyear2start = 1939 |coachyear2end = 42 |coachgames2 = 32 |coachwins2 = 22 |coachdraws2 = 0 |coachlosses2 = 10 |source = [http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile.aspx?fname=PlayerProfile.aspx&QStr=1263 Yesterday's Hero] [http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/Jerry_Brien/summary.html RLP] }}
'''Jerry Brien''' (born in [[Sydney, Australia]]) was a [[rugby league]] footballer and coach. He played for the [[Western Suburbs Magpies]], [[St. George Dragons]] and for the [[New South Wales Rugby League team]]. He also coached the [[Bulldogs Rugby League Football Club|Canterbury-Bankstown]] club.
==Career== In 1925, Brien was chosen to play for [[New South Wales state rugby league team|New South Wales]] although he was only playing for the [[Western Suburbs Magpies|Magpies]] reserve grade,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerry Brien|url=http://www.yesterdayshero.com.au/PlayerProfile.aspx?fname=PlayerProfile.aspx&QStr=1263|accessdate=21 September 2010| publisher=''yesterday's hero''}}</ref> and had played just a handful of first grade games since his debut in 1923.
Brien represented NSW again in 1928, and was selected to represent [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] in the second test against England, but an injury suffered playing for Wests stopped him from making his international debut.<ref name="encyc">{{cite book| last1=Whiticker|first1=Alan|last2=Hudson|first2=Glen|title=The Encyclopedia of Rugby League Players|year=2007|publisher=''Gary Allen Pty Ltd''|location=[[Wetherill Park, New South Wales]]|isbn=978-1-877082-93-1|pages=53-53}}</ref>
After 6 seasons with the Magpies, Brien joined the [[St. George Dragons]] for 4 games in 1929.
After his retirement as a player, Brien began coaching, including stints with South Grafton in 1932 <ref>{{cite news|publisher=''Sydney Morning Herald''|title=Football Rugby League|author=|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16853608?searchTerm=jerry+brien|accessdate=22 September 2010|date=6 April 1932}}</ref> & Cowra in 1933.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=''Sydney Morning Herald''|title=Rugby League|author=|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16971299?searchTerm=jerry+brien|accessdate=22 September 2010|date=15 April 1933}}</ref> In 1937, Brien returned to coach the Magpies for the eight games of the shortened season. In 1939, he took over as coach at [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs|Bulldogs]] for a season, and returned to be at the helm when they won their second premiership in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jerry Brien|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/Jerry_Brien/summary.html|accessdate=21 September 2010| publisher=''Rugby League Project''}}</ref>
By 1947, Brien was NSW coach and one of their selectors.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=''Sydney Morning Herald''|title=State League Team Goes North To-day|author=Tom Goodman|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18035770?searchTerm=jerry+brien|accessdate=22 September 2010|date=18 July 1947}}</ref> Later, he became an Australian selector,<ref name="encyc" /> but was dropped as a NSW selector in March 1951, making him inelegible to fill the national role.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=''Sydney Morning Herald''|title=League Drops State Selector|author=|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18203716|accessdate=21 September 2010|date=13 March 1951}}</ref>
